    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so if the concrete is mostly just handling the crushing force, what's actually happening inside it when there's a bending moment? like, if the tension is pulling on one side, how does the rebar actually interact with the concrete internally to prevent it from just snapping?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great question! Under a bending moment, concrete near tension zones typically fails in shear, causing cracks to form. These cracks are then flexed around the rebar within the concrete. The steel rebar, owing to its high tensile strength, takes on the tension from the side experiencing the bending force.\n\nAs the concrete cracks, the rebar elements resist the tensile forces by yielding slightly. This ultimately prevents the concrete from snapping by allowing both materials to work together, accommodating the stress load. Because steel rebar does not crack or break easily under tension, it ensures the structural integrity of the concrete under bending moments, creating a composite material that can withstand greater forces than either alone.",
      "source": "target",
